BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:_6XU_Jx9v6YBwftdcr9E6
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260326T160827Z
DTSTART:20260404T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-04T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-04T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:h-vM2dmmzNB-aTG8jpj22
SUMMARY:Earth Month Event | Restoration at Gallagher Hill Open Space
DTSTAMP:20260326T160827Z
DTSTART:20260404T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Celebrate Earth Month through Volunteering in your Local Park!\
	n\nGallagher Hill Open Space is a beautiful park with old trees\, a thrivi
	ng stream\, and plenty of native plant and animal life. A lot of the park 
	is unfortunately being overgrown with blackberry and ivy\, threating the h
	ealth of this vital ecosystem. Situated above the freeway Gallagher Hil l 
	is an important respite of nature that is well worth protecting. Come jo i
	n us for a park clean-up where we will be removing ivy. It will be a grea 
	t chance to get your hands in the dirt\, learn about native plants and our
	 local forests\, and work alongside neighbors and friends! \n\nNo experien
	ce necessary and all ages welcome\; gloves and tools are provided. Please 
	note: we require participants aged 14 and under to volunteer with a pare n
	t or guardian at a ratio of 1 adult to 3 kids.\n\nWhen: Saturday\,  April 
	4th\, 10am-1pm\n\nWhere: Gallagher Hill Open Space off of Shorewood Dr\, f
	ollow VOLUNTEER EVENT Signs \n\nWhat to bring: Dress for the weather in cl
	oth es you don't mind getting dirty \\(think: long pants\, boots or sneake
	rs\\). Bring a water bottle. Small snacks\, gloves\, and tools will be pro
	vided.\n\nRegistration: https://volunteersignup.org/KMTKY\n\nhttps://seato
	day.6amcity.com/events/#/details/earth-month-event-restoration-at-gallaghe
	r-hill-open-space/18066407/2026-04-04T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Ci
	vic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/earth-month-event-restora
	tion-at-gallagher-hill-open-space/18066407/2026-04-04T00
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT3H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:vHI_VqceOsPkUix-dkKbT
SUMMARY:Samantha Yun Wall: What We Leave Behind
DTSTAMP:20260326T160827Z
DTSTART:20260404T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Samantha Yun Wall’s new paintings use overlapping silhouettes o
	f female figures as portals to unknown spaces and different temporal realm
	s. Impetus for the new body of work is a Korean folk tale in which the Pas
	que flower is symbolic of a grandmother who passed away without the loving
	 care of her grandchildren. It is a story of melancholy\, loss\, and remem
	brance. The delicate hair on the flower’s stem differentiates it\, and the
	 artist gives the plant a surreal aspect in some of her paintings\, replac
	ing the flower’s center with a watchful eye.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.c
	om/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we-leave-behind/18026187/2026-0
	4-04T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we
	-leave-behind/18026187/2026-04-04T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
